			<h1 class="font-heading text-3xl md:text-[40px] font-bold text-charcoal-900 leading-tight mb-4">
				North Carolina Preneed Regulations Explained in Plain English
			</h1>
			<p class="text-charcoal-500 mb-2">By <strong class="text-charcoal-900">Duane Cutlip</strong>, Licensed Preneed Funeral Director | March 2026</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
		<Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Insights', href: '/insights' }, { label: 'NC Preneed Regulations' }]} />

		<article class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700">

			<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
				North Carolina's preneed funeral regulations are governed by N.C.G.S. Chapter 90, Article 13D — specifically sections 90-210.60 through 90-210.73. These statutes establish the licensing requirements, trust and insurance requirements, consumer protections, and enforcement mechanisms that every funeral home and preneed sales agent in North Carolina must follow.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The problem? The statutes are written in legal language that most funeral directors didn't go to school to interpret. This article translates the key provisions into plain English, with practical guidance for funeral homes that want to stay compliant, protect their families, and avoid problems with the NC Board of Funeral Service.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				<em>Disclaimer: This article is educational, not legal advice. Consult with an attorney for guidance specific to your situation. Statutes and rules are subject to change — always verify against the current published law.</em>
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Who Needs a Preneed License?</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Under N.C.G.S. 90-210.61, anyone who sells or offers to sell preneed funeral contracts in North Carolina must hold a preneed funeral establishment license issued by the North Carolina Board of Funeral Service. This applies to:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li>Funeral homes that sell preneed contracts directly to consumers</li>
				<li>Third-party preneed sales organizations that sell on behalf of funeral homes</li>
				<li>Individual preneed sales agents operating under a licensed establishment</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The individual selling the preneed contract must also be licensed as a <strong>preneed sales agent</strong> (sometimes called a preneed licensee) or be a licensed funeral director or funeral service licensee. You cannot legally sell preneed in NC without proper licensing — period.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Application Process</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The application for a preneed funeral establishment license is filed with the NC Board of Funeral Service. The application requires:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li>Proof of a valid funeral establishment license (or association with one)</li>
				<li>A <strong>$50,000 surety bond</strong> — this bond protects consumers in the event the funeral home fails to perform under its preneed contracts</li>
				<li>A <strong>$150 application fee</strong></li>
				<li>Designation of a responsible preneed licensee</li>
				<li>Documentation of trust or insurance arrangements for preneed funds</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The $50,000 surety bond is one of the most significant requirements. It serves as a financial backstop — if the funeral home closes, fails to honor contracts, or mishandles preneed funds, the bond provides a recovery mechanism for affected consumers. The bond must be maintained continuously; a lapse in bonding can result in immediate suspension of the preneed license.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Trust Requirements: What Must Be Held in Trust</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For trust-funded preneed contracts (as opposed to insurance-funded — more on that below), North Carolina law requires that a specific portion of the preneed funds be deposited into a trust account. Here's how it works:
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">The 10% Trustee Retention Allowance</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Under N.C.G.S. 90-210.63, the funeral home (as trustee or through a designated trustee) is permitted to retain up to <strong>10% of the preneed contract payments</strong> as an allowance for sales, administrative, and trust management expenses. The remaining 90% (or more) must be deposited into the trust.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For example, if a family pays $10,000 for a preneed contract:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li>Up to $1,000 (10%) may be retained by the funeral home</li>
				<li>At least $9,000 (90%) must be deposited into the preneed trust</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The trust must be held in a federally insured financial institution in North Carolina. The trust funds must be invested prudently, and the funeral home must maintain accurate records of all deposits, withdrawals, and investment activity.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Trust Accounting and Reporting</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The funeral home must maintain individual trust records for each preneed contract. The NC Board of Funeral Service can audit these records at any time, and periodic reporting is required. Trust accounting is one of the most common areas of compliance failure — and one of the first things the Board examines during an inspection.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Insurance-Funded Preneed: How It Differs</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Insurance-funded preneed contracts are an alternative to trust-funded contracts. Instead of depositing payments into a trust, the preneed contract is backed by a life insurance policy on the purchaser's life. The funeral home is named as the beneficiary (or assignee) of the policy, and the death benefit is used to pay for the funeral services at the time of need.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Insurance-funded preneed has become the dominant model in North Carolina for several reasons:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li><strong>No trust accounting burden:</strong> The insurance carrier handles the investment and record-keeping, eliminating the compliance overhead of maintaining trust accounts.</li>
				<li><strong>Medicaid exemption:</strong> Irrevocable insurance-funded preneed contracts are generally exempt from Medicaid asset calculations in NC — a critical benefit for families concerned about Medicaid eligibility.</li>
				<li><strong>Growth potential:</strong> Many preneed insurance policies include a growth rider that increases the death benefit over time, helping to offset funeral cost inflation.</li>
				<li><strong>Insolvency protection:</strong> The death benefit is guaranteed by the insurance carrier (subject to state guaranty fund limits), providing an additional layer of consumer protection beyond the surety bond.</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				However, insurance-funded preneed is still subject to NC preneed regulations. The funeral home must be licensed for preneed sales, the contract must comply with disclosure requirements, and the insurance product itself must be approved for preneed use in North Carolina.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Consumer Protection Provisions</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				North Carolina's preneed statutes include robust consumer protection measures. Funeral homes and preneed agents should know these inside and out — both to stay compliant and because they represent genuine value propositions for families considering preneed planning.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">100% Transferability</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Under NC law, preneed funeral contracts are <strong>fully transferable</strong>. A consumer can transfer their preneed contract to a different funeral home at any time. The original funeral home must release the trust funds (or cooperate with the insurance policy assignment) to the new provider. This ensures that families are never locked into a funeral home they're unhappy with.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For funeral homes, this means retention matters. If you're losing contracts to transfers, it's a signal that your customer relationships need attention. It also means that competing for existing preneed business is legitimate — but ethical practices and professionalism are expected.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Refund Rights</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Consumers have the right to cancel their preneed contract and receive a refund. For trust-funded contracts, the refund is generally the amount held in trust (the 90%+ that was deposited). The 10% retention allowance is typically not refundable — it was retained to cover sales and administrative costs already incurred.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For insurance-funded contracts, the refund mechanism depends on the insurance policy's terms — typically the cash surrender value of the policy. Families should understand this distinction before signing.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Disclosure Requirements</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				NC law requires specific disclosures to the consumer at the time of sale, including:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li>A clear description of the funeral goods and services included in the contract</li>
				<li>The total price and payment terms</li>
				<li>Whether the contract is revocable or irrevocable</li>
				<li>The consumer's right to transfer or cancel</li>
				<li>How the funds will be held (trust or insurance)</li>
				<li>What happens if the funeral home goes out of business</li>
				<li>The name and contact information for the NC Board of Funeral Service</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				These disclosures must be in writing and signed by the consumer. Missing or incomplete disclosures are a common compliance finding during Board examinations and can result in disciplinary action.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Recent Changes: NC HB 1003 (2025)</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				In 2025, the North Carolina General Assembly passed House Bill 1003, introducing several notable changes to the preneed regulatory framework. Here are the key provisions funeral homes need to know:
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Trust-to-Insurance Conversion</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				HB 1003 establishes a formal process for converting existing trust-funded preneed contracts to insurance-funded contracts. This is significant for funeral homes that have legacy trust-funded books — the conversion can reduce administrative burden, improve Medicaid protection for families, and provide growth potential through insurance policy riders.
			</p>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The conversion process requires:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li>Written consent from the contract holder</li>
				<li>Disclosure of any changes to the contract terms resulting from the conversion</li>
				<li>Use of an insurance product approved for preneed use in NC</li>
				<li>Proper handling of trust fund disbursement during the transition</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Religious Practices Provisions</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The bill includes new provisions recognizing and accommodating religious practices in preneed funeral arrangements. This codifies the importance of documenting religious preferences — such as timing requirements, washing rituals, or specific burial orientations — as part of the preneed contract. Funeral homes should update their preneed intake forms to capture this information.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Transportation Agreements</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				HB 1003 clarifies the regulatory treatment of transportation agreements within preneed contracts. This is particularly relevant for funeral homes in rural areas or those serving families whose place of death may be different from the location of services. The bill provides clearer guidelines for how transportation costs can be included and funded within preneed contracts.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Compliance Checklist for Funeral Homes</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				Use this checklist to verify your funeral home's preneed compliance. This is not exhaustive, but it covers the most common areas of non-compliance that the NC Board of Funeral Service examines:
			</p>

			<div class="bg-linen rounded-xl p-6 my-6 border border-border-light">
				<h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-charcoal-900 mb-4">Preneed Compliance Checklist</h3>
				<ul class="space-y-3">
					{[
						'Preneed funeral establishment license is current and displayed',
						'All preneed sales agents hold valid licenses or are licensed funeral directors',
						'$50,000 surety bond is active and in good standing',
						'Written preneed contracts include all required disclosures',
						'Consumer signatures are on file for every active contract',
						'Trust funds are deposited in a federally insured NC financial institution',
						'Trust deposits meet or exceed 90% of contract payments received',
						'Individual trust account records are maintained for each contract',
						'Insurance-funded contracts use NC-approved preneed insurance products',
						'Insurance policy assignments/beneficiary designations are properly documented',
						'Refund and transfer procedures are documented and followed consistently',
						'Records of all preneed contracts sold, transferred, cancelled, and fulfilled are current',
						'Compliance with HB 1003 provisions (trust-to-insurance conversions, disclosures)',
						'Religious practice preferences are documented where applicable',
						'Annual reporting to the NC Board of Funeral Service is current',
					].map((item) => (
						<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
							<span class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 rounded border-2 border-charcoal-300"></span>
							<span>{item}</span>
						</li>
					))}
				</ul>
			</div>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">What Happens During a Board Examination</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The NC Board of Funeral Service conducts periodic examinations of funeral homes to verify compliance with preneed regulations. Here's what to expect:
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Notice and Scheduling</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The Board typically provides advance notice of an examination, though unannounced inspections are possible — particularly if a complaint has been filed. Examinations can be triggered by routine scheduling, consumer complaints, or concerns identified during previous inspections.
			</p>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">What They Review</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				During an examination, Board inspectors will typically review:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li><strong>Licensing:</strong> Verification that the funeral establishment and all preneed agents hold current, valid licenses.</li>
				<li><strong>Surety bond:</strong> Confirmation that the $50,000 bond is active.</li>
				<li><strong>Contract files:</strong> A sample of preneed contracts will be pulled and reviewed for completeness, proper disclosures, and consumer signatures.</li>
				<li><strong>Trust accounts:</strong> Bank statements, deposit records, and individual trust ledgers will be examined for accuracy and compliance with the 90% deposit requirement.</li>
				<li><strong>Insurance documentation:</strong> For insurance-funded contracts, the inspector will verify that policies are in force, beneficiary designations are correct, and the insurance products are approved for preneed use in NC.</li>
				<li><strong>Fulfillment records:</strong> How completed preneed contracts were honored — were services delivered as documented?</li>
				<li><strong>Cancellation/refund records:</strong> Were refunds processed correctly and in a timely manner?</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 class="font-heading text-xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-8 mb-3">Potential Outcomes</h3>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				If the examination identifies compliance issues, the Board may issue:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li><strong>A letter of caution:</strong> For minor, first-time issues that the funeral home can correct quickly.</li>
				<li><strong>A consent order:</strong> A formal agreement requiring the funeral home to take specific corrective actions within a defined timeframe.</li>
				<li><strong>Disciplinary action:</strong> For serious or repeated violations, the Board can impose fines, suspend licenses, or revoke licenses entirely.</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				The best strategy is prevention. Maintain your records meticulously, conduct internal audits of your preneed program at least annually, and address any issues proactively before the Board finds them.
			</p>

			<h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal-900 mt-12 mb-4">Key Statute References</h2>
			<p class="leading-relaxed">
				For those who want to read the actual statutes, here are the key sections of N.C.G.S. Chapter 90, Article 13D:
			</p>
			<ul class="space-y-2 my-4">
				<li><strong>90-210.60:</strong> Definitions</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.61:</strong> Preneed funeral establishment license requirements</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.62:</strong> Preneed sales agent licensing</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.63:</strong> Trust fund requirements and trustee retention allowance</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.64:</strong> Insurance-funded preneed contracts</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.65:</strong> Consumer disclosures</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.66:</strong> Transferability and refund rights</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.67:</strong> Surety bond requirements</li>
				<li><strong>90-210.68-73:</strong> Enforcement, penalties, and Board authority</li>
			</ul>

